Return to the very American ideal of labour rights as human rights
Congressmen Keith Ellison and John Lewis have put forward a bill to establish the organization of trade unions as a civil right.
"As unions die, so die the middle class jobs," said Ellison, a Minnesota Democrat and Deputy Chairman of the Progressive Caucus in Congress.
That’s why I proudly present the Employee Empowerment Act together with civil rights icon John Lewis.
This groundbreaking law gives workers the same legal opportunities in the case of discrimination based on the organization of unions as in other forms of discrimination - and thus stops anti-union forces.
Complementing the National Labour Code to provide a way for workers exposed to discrimination to organize a trade union representation, to sue for justice before a civil court — and to receive damages or penalties — is a sensible and necessary initiative.
But it is certainly not a radical initiative - at least not according to American standards.
In fact, the best way to understand what Ellison, Lewis, and the other sponsors of their bill are proposing is to link back to a very American idea.
Despite the setbacks that unions have faced in recent years—in Wisconsin, Michigan, and other states across the country—Americans have once encouraged countries around the world to recognize, expand, and uphold labor rights.
There was a time when millions of Americans still remember when this country called democracy, freedom of speech, freedom of the press, and the right of association in one breath.
When the United States occupied Japan after World War II, General Douglas Mac Arthur and his staff encouraged the country to pass a constitution to ensure that the militarized autocracy of Hedki Tojos was replaced by democracy.
Fully aware that the workers and their trade unions played a role in the creation of a new Japan, they used a language that explicitly recognized that "the workers' rights to union and common negotiation and action are guaranteed."
When the United States occupied Germany after World War II, General Dwight David Eisenhower and his staff urged the Germans to write a constitution that would ensure that Adolf Hitler’s fascism was replaced by a strong democracy.
In recognition of the fact that the workers would have to organize themselves and raise their voices in the new nation, the Germans added a clause explicitly stating: "The right to form associations in order to secure and improve labor and economic conditions is guaranteed to every individual and to every occupation or trade.
Agreements that restrict or aim to restrict this right are null and void; measures aimed at it are unlawful.
When former First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt presided over the International Human Rights Commission, which drafted the Universal Declaration of Human Rights as adopted by the United Nations in 1948 as a global agreement, Roosevelt and the other authors added a guarantee that “everyone has the right to form or join unions to protect their interests.”
For generations, Americans have accepted the basic premise that labour rights are human rights.
When this country advised other countries on how to form civilian and democratic societies, Americans declared that the right to form a trade union – and that this union could then participate in collective bargaining as an equal partner with corporations and government agencies – must be protected.
After these rights have come under attack in America, it is indeed very wise to rethink the American ideal that the working population must have the right to unite and to make themselves heard in a free and open society.
As Pastor Martin Luther King Jr. said fifty years ago:
History is a great teacher.
Now everyone knows that the workers’ movement did not limit the strength of the nation, but enlarged it.
By raising the living standards of millions of people, labor has miraculously created a market for industry and raised the entire nation to unimaginable levels of production.
Those who attack the work forget these simple truths, but history preserves them.
History remembers, and we should.
The formal recognition of labour rights as human rights - and the extension of the protection of civil rights as protection against discrimination in the creation of employee representations - is long overdue.
Keith Ellison and John Lewis renew the ideals that have made America great in the past and fulfilled the promise of democracy.
Judge temporarily stops law that could force all abortion clinics in Louisiana to close
A U.S. federal judge temporarily halted the implementation of a law in Louisiana on Sunday, which lawyers say would have led to the closure of all five abortion clinics in the state.
This measure, which was enacted by Bobby Jindal, governor of Louisiana, in June and is due to enter into force on Sept. 1, would force doctors who perform abortions to acquire a patient admission right at a hospital within a 30-mile radius of their practice.
However, the judge’s decision means that doctors can continue to legally perform abortions for the time being while applying for such a right.
"The plaintiffs can continue to work in accordance with the law as they endeavour to obtain these rights," Federal Judge John deGravelles wrote in his verdict.
Within a month, a hearing is scheduled for the judge to bring about a more permanent decision for the law.
Abortion advocates welcomed the decision, the latest in a series of judgments against similar measures, saying doctors gained more time to gain hospital admission rights.
“Today’s decision means the women in Louisiana are escaping a subtle law that wants to take away their health and their rights,” said Nancy Northup, president and chair of the Center for Reproductive Rights, which had sued on behalf of three of the state’s five clinics to stop the law.
It was not immediately clear whether the judgment also extended to the doctors from the two clinics who had not joined the lawsuit and had also applied for the right of admission.
Louisiana is one of 11 states that have passed similar laws, with courts in Alabama and Mississippi recently declaring such measures unconstitutional.
Key points of a law in Texas that would have forced most of the clinics remaining in the state to close were halted by a federal judge on Friday.
Abortion advocates and the American College of Ostretricians and Gynecologists, as well as the American Medical Association, agree that admission rights require unnecessary restrictions from doctors.
Opponents of abortion argue that the measures are designed to protect women’s health, although some also welcomed the impact of clinic closures.
Only one doctor who performs abortions in Louisiana has patient-entry rights, the Center for Reproductive Rights said.
If all the other doctors in the state were forced to stop performing abortions, this doctor, fearing for his safety, would stop performing the operation, the group said.
In their argument against the verdict, representatives of the state of Louisiana said they would not punish doctors for performing abortions while their requests for patient record rights were still pending.
