A British woman says she thought she would die as a result of a misdiagnosis for many years.
Karin Rodgers lived almost her entire adolescence in the belief that she had only a few years left to live after being diagnosed with another disease.
She actually suffered from Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease (CMT), a group of inherited disorders that damage the nerves outside of the brain and spinal cord.
Charity CMT UK said misdiagnosis is a common problem in people with CMT because so little is known about this disease.
Approximately 23,000 people in the UK are presumably suffering from CMT, which can lead to motor disorders such as muscle weakness, an uncertain gait and curved toes.
The disease is incurable and progressive, which means that the symptoms will worsen over time.
When Rodgers was 13, she believed she was suffering from Friedreich ataxia (FA), a disease with very poor survival chances.
Rodgers thought she would be in a wheelchair before she turned 18, and die before her 30th birthday.
