I fell down all the time and everything took longer for me.
I could never ride roller skates or skateboards with the other kids and was often teased at school because of my way of walking and running.
Rodgers said that at the age of 13, after several operations to relieve her Achilles tendon and stretch her feet, she saw her medical record when her doctor left the room and read that she was suffering from FA.
"I felt guilty because I had been curious, so I didn't tell anyone that, but I went home, looked for the disease in the library, and wrote to the FA Society," she said.
When I received an answer, I was shocked and panicked terribly.
I thought I would be in a wheelchair at 18 and die at 25, and slowly lose all my skills in between.
I did it all by myself and planned my own funeral.
She said when she turned 17, she realized that her abilities had not decreased as much as she had imagined and asked her doctor.
He just got up and hugged me and said, "My dear, I don't think you have that, otherwise you'd already be in a wheelchair."
I think you have something far less life-threatening.
After several genetic tests, her CMT was diagnosed.
