We showed a powerful tribe during our puzzle of the summer series "Mein Stück vom Rhöner Glück" last Friday.
Several of these tree giants still exist in the district, the specimen shown is the "Geißruheiche" above Unterweißenbrunn.
A bumpy footpath leads up to the 600-year-old oak.
It passes Koppeln, basalt stone piles and basalt stone seas.
A bit below the quarry from Bauersberg, a kilometre north of the road to Weisbach, there it stands.
The natural monument looks vital, it protrudes above the other trees of the surrounding area and is reminiscent of an American sequoia with a circumference of over eight meters.
A little Buddha on a stump suggests that it is a spiritual or mystical place.
But despite intensive research, there were only clues to the origin of the name.
Dr. Wolfgang Schneider has consulted the Bischofsheimer Archiv and interviewed older people from Unterweißenbrunn to find out what their relationship with the Geißruheiche is.
The result of his research remained the rather sober explanation for the name.
According to this, up to about 80 years ago, the goat herders drove their animals from Unterweißenbrunn to the meadows that had been laboriously cleared and stoned.
At the foot of the tree are said to have rested the animal keepers exhausted by the ascent.
In the meantime, the area has regained its importance, because in the meadows actually graze goat herds again.
The area has also been declared the core zone of the biosphere reserve, Schneider further found out.
However, you should be careful when entering the stone collections, because the basalt warmed by the sun is also a popular place to stay for otters.
A hiking trail leads from Unterweißenbrunn to the tree, but it is somewhat hidden.
Further trails are signposted, which ascend in the direction of Hochrhön and invite to an extended hike.
