After weeks of turmoil, Italy’s Prime Minister and current EU Chairman, Matteo Renzi, has enforced the nomination of his Foreign Minister Federica Mogherini as head of EU foreign policy against strong conservative resistance at the EU special summit last week, she will succeed Britain’s Catherine Ashton.
Renzi considers, as the pro-government daily La Repubblica reflects, the appointment of his Mogherini, who is also a favorite in the government team, as a strengthening of the position of the Social Democrats and his own in the EU.
He also expects a boost for his "reform package" in Italy.
Last but not least, Renzi hopes to calm down the left-wing party base that is constantly rebelling against him, because Mogherini is assigned to it, albeit in a more moderate way.
In contrast to the conservative representatives with Commission President Jean-Claude Juncker and Poland nominated as Council President Donald Tusk, the prevailing opinion in Rome is thus to establish a political balance.
The chief diplomat of the EU will also be the deputy of Commission President Juncker.
The pending approval of the European Parliament is deemed to be certain.
Otherwise, President Giorgio Napolitano would hardly have called the nomination of the 41-year-old politician of the ruling Democratic Party (PD) an "important recognition" of Italy's role in the EU.
La Repubblica spreads optimism that Mogherini, which has been proven in leading party offices for almost two decades and known for her ambition, will be able to cope with the "enormous challenges".
The native Roman woman is married and has two daughters.
In 1996, she began her career as a political scientist in the youth organization of the then Democratici di Sinistra (Left Democrats), which in 2008 joined forces with the Catholic centre party Margherita to form today's Social Democratic PD.
In 1999, Mogherini became Vice-President of the European Community Organisation of Socialist Youth (European Young Socialists) for three years.
When she was elected to the Left Democrat Party Council in 2001, she joined the high party politics and worked in the foreign policy department, whose head she soon became.
It occupied traditional focal points of Italian foreign policy such as the Middle East, became known by studies on NATO deployment in Afghanistan, in which Italy is involved with a contingent of troops, maintained contacts with the Social Democrats in Europe and with the Democrats in the US.
Since 2008, she has been a member of the Chamber of Deputies, where she is an expert on defence and European and international affairs.
When Renzi became prime minister in February 2014, he appointed Mogherini as his foreign minister.
If the PD today has a better relationship with the strong peace movement in the country, which contributed to the party’s over 40 percent vote in the EU elections in May, then, as noted in PD circles, Federica Mogherini has a share of it.
The allegations in Brussels that the new EU foreign minister has too little diplomatic experience, that is, lack of substance, are countered in the PD.
In Brussels, especially by Poland and the Baltic members, Mogherini's suspiciously realistic accents on the crisis in Ukraine are being pursued and defamed as a "Russia-friendly course".
It endorses the South Stream pipeline operated by the Russian company Gasprom, through which Russian natural gas will be transported directly to southern Europe bypassing Ukraine, which also serves to secure Italy’s energy.
After Renzi took office as EU President in July, Mogherini traveled to Moscow for her first state visit.
Photos they showed with Putin at the shake-hands were taken in Brussels with outrage, as well as inviting the Kremlin chief for October to a Milan economic summit.
