Putin asks Kiev to start "state talks" with eastern Ukraine
Russian President Vladimir Putin demanded on Sunday that the Ukrainian government stop fighting the separatists in the east of the country and immediately begin negotiations on the “state” of the renegade region.
His spokesman Dimitri Peskov later made clear that Putin did not mean that the territory of eastern Ukraine under the control of the separatists would become a part of Russia, but that his status with Ukraine would need to be redefined in order to give the Russian-speaking region the power to represent its rights and interests.
However, Putin’s appeal to the Kiev government to negotiate on an equal footing with the pro-Russian insurgents fits with the strategy he has apparently pursued since the start of the riots five months ago: help the separatists take territory and pressure on the Ukrainian government to enable the newly proclaimed Novorossia region to gain de facto independence for an alliance with Russia instead of the West.
In an interview with the state television channel Channel One, Putin condemned the Ukrainian military campaign to recapture separatist-held areas in the eastern regions of Donetsk and Luhansk, which were captured in March and April after Moscow annexed the Ukrainian peninsula of Crimea on March 18.
The Kremlin and the separatists have recently referred to the occupied territory as "Novorossia" or "New Russia", a term reminiscent of the pre-revolutionary splendor of the Russian empire.
Putin pointed out that all those who, in the wake of the campaigns of Ukrainian politicians for the Oct. 26 elections and while government groups are attacking civilian communities in the separatist-held areas are hoping for soon-to-be peace talks are “capped in their illusions,” Itar-Tass reported.
"We need to immediately engage in detailed talks, not only on technical issues, but also on the political organization of society and the state status of South-East Ukraine, in order to safeguard the interests of the people living there," he said.
Peskov said Putin’s reference to statehood should be seen in the context of the greater autonomy discussed for months by the Kiev leadership to dispel fears in Russian-speaking areas that their cultural and linguistic rights are at risk.
Only the Ukrainian government can grant the necessary autonomy to the eastern regions, Peskov said.
It is not a matter of negotiations between Ukraine and Russia, Peskov said, "because it is not a conflict between Russia and Ukraine, but an internal conflict in Ukraine."
The Kremlin spokesman’s clarification to correct the “misinterpretation” of Putin’s remarks underlined Russia’s claim to leadership in dealing with the separatist rebellion in the East as opposed to the direct annexation of Crimea, where the majority of the 2 million residents are ethnic Russians.
Moscow would have far greater difficulty annexing the Donetsk and Luhansk regions in eastern Ukraine, as most of the 6.5 million inhabitants are not Russians and polls from the pre-conflict period revealed a broad majority for staying in Ukraine.
The autonomy addressed by Russian diplomats on international forums would give the regional governments in Ukraine power to negotiate their own trade agreements and external relations, thus giving the Kremlin de facto control over an area connecting the Russian territory with Crimea.
The peninsula in the Black Sea, annexed five months ago, is the home port for the majority of the Russian navy, as well as an important trading port and historic coastal region.
The regions between the Rostov region in Russia and Crimea are also rich in mines, factories and foundries that produce important components for the Russian military.
Ukrainian President Petro Poroshenko, in his inauguration speech on June 7, suggested that Ukrainian legislation should consider amendments to the Constitution, after new elections, which would give the respective territories greater control over their finances and the status of languages.
But his notion of autonomy seems to be in sharp contrast to those of the Kremlin and the separatist rebels, whose arming and incitement Moscow is accused of.
Putin’s last call to Kiev to negotiate with the separatist leaders on an equal footing followed a further advance of the rebels last week after Russian troops and tanks invaded eastern Ukraine via the previously peaceful region along the Azov Sea.
The Russian-backed separatists took control of Novoasovsk in a gesture that, according to fears of Ukrainian security officials, is the first step in a campaign to take over the strategic coastal region up to Crimea.
For this reason, massive civilian and military preparations have begun to fortify Mariupol, a 500,000-population steel-industrial port located between Novoasovsk and the narrow access to the Crimean peninsula.
Speaking at a meeting of EU leaders in Brussels on Saturday, Poroshenko urged action to prevent another Russian aggression against Ukraine, a former Soviet republic that has been independent for 23 years.
"We are at a point where there is no turning back," Poroshenko warned.
Thousands of foreign troops and hundreds of foreign tanks are now on the territory of Ukraine.
The EU summit decided no concrete actions, the leadership demanded the draft further sanctions against Russia, which should come into force in the event of an unspecified escalation of the Ukraine crisis.
Ukrainian soldiers had to withdraw from their positions in Ilovajsk after two Russian tank columns and 1,000 soldiers invaded the Donetsk region last week to support the besieged separatists, said Colonel Andriy Lysenko, spokesman for the Ukrainian National Security and Defence Council Reports on Saturday in Kiev.
The first presumably 63 Ukrainian soldiers trapped by the Russian invasion of Ilovaysk were exchanged on Sunday for 10 Russian paratroopers captured on Ukrainian territory a week ago, Lysenko said on Sunday.
